00:25:21,775 --> 00:25:25,819
which isn't impossible because SNK does have really hardcore fans.

483
00:25:26,419 --> 00:25:32,364
They just tend to be fans of the 90s and more current SNK content, not the 80s stuff.

484
00:25:32,424 --> 00:25:37,048
But this gave us an opportunity to say, hey, SNK fans, here's the roots of this company.

485
00:25:38,895 --> 00:25:45,402
We also, it was our duty, we thought to sort of alter the gameplay of some of these games

486
00:25:45,442 --> 00:25:50,907
to modernize it in a way that was more understandable and to reinterpret the controls, which I'll

487
00:25:50,927 --> 00:25:51,748
get to in a minute.

488
00:25:52,509 --> 00:25:55,712
But first I got a video up here somewhere.

489
00:25:55,832 --> 00:25:56,393
There we go.

490
00:25:58,094 --> 00:25:58,415
All right.

491
00:26:03,252 --> 00:26:09,602
So this is a demonstration of what we're kind of known for our extra material in these games,

492
00:26:09,642 --> 00:26:13,628
right? We do a little bit more in the games. We kind of give you the original packaging artwork

493
00:26:13,708 --> 00:26:16,112
and things like that. And in SNK's case,

494
00:26:18,275 --> 00:26:19,976
They made like 60 games in the 80s.

495
00:26:21,277 --> 00:26:24,278
We'd still be working on this project if we did all 60 games.

496
00:26:24,578 --> 00:26:25,859
So we kind of curated the collection.

497
00:26:25,899 --> 00:26:29,861
But but I wanted to at least show what all the other games were. Right.

498
00:26:29,901 --> 00:26:33,043
So this is actually a complete list of every game that SNK game

499
00:26:33,163 --> 00:26:34,723
that SNK had done in the 80s.

500
00:26:35,304 --> 00:26:36,504
And for each one of these,

501
00:26:38,045 --> 00:26:41,667
if if art exists, we put it in there like it literally exists in the world.

502
00:26:42,147 --> 00:26:46,069
You can, of course, do your zooming and stuff and and and and go in on there.

503
00:26:46,891 --> 00:26:50,501
We got the screen test of the games, but each one of these also has a little bit of a history

504
00:26:50,541 --> 00:26:53,550
lesson and it kind of comes across as like...

505
00:26:54,742 --> 00:26:57,944
an interactive art book about the history of SNK.

506
00:26:58,345 --> 00:27:01,326
And this was our way of capturing that

507
00:27:01,366 --> 00:27:04,168
because a lot of this history has just never been talked

508
00:27:04,228 --> 00:27:05,729
about even by SNK.

509
00:27:06,630 --> 00:27:09,111
A lot of these guys are not getting any younger.

510
00:27:09,552 --> 00:27:13,534
And so we wanted to sort of educate the consumer

511
00:27:13,614 --> 00:27:15,195
on what this company was and give you

512
00:27:15,235 --> 00:27:18,637
the definitive package, like here was SNK in the 80s.

513
00:27:19,478 --> 00:27:22,380
So that was our approach with the museum content.

514
00:27:25,128 --> 00:27:28,589
But we also added a feature that...

515
00:27:28,609 --> 00:27:31,209
Oh wait, that is the same video.

516
00:27:31,409 --> 00:27:32,549
That is not what we want to do.

517
00:27:36,370 --> 00:27:37,750
Excuse me a moment, folks.

518
00:27:50,053 --> 00:27:51,593
Okay, so this is sort of the game selection menu.

519
00:27:53,670 --> 00:28:02,095
So another thing we did with this collection is that for all the titles in here, like POW,

520
00:28:02,235 --> 00:28:05,136
for example, we included all the regional versions of it.

521
00:28:05,637 --> 00:28:09,359
And we included the home console version as well, if there was one, which I think is really

522
00:28:09,379 --> 00:28:10,339
important actually, because it...

523
00:28:12,140 --> 00:28:17,842
tells you a little bit more about that game to know how they approached a home version of it.

524
00:28:17,882 --> 00:28:22,924
Like in SNK's case, most of their home versions actually added features that the arcade games

525
00:28:22,944 --> 00:28:28,746
didn't have, made them a little more RPG-like even. And even internally, this was a little

526
00:28:28,766 --> 00:28:32,307
bit of a struggle because I think that a lot of companies are like, oh, why would you do the

527
00:28:32,447 --> 00:28:36,849
inferior version of the game, right? But for us, it's like, no, we're historians, right? We're

528
00:28:36,869 --> 00:28:40,970
trying to explain what your company was and we should include all of that stuff.

529
00:28:42,191 --> 00:28:45,176
Luckily, they went for it.

530
00:28:46,918 --> 00:28:48,300
But a feature that we added...

531
00:28:50,127 --> 00:28:52,890
I don't think it's crazy to say that people like watching people play video games.

532
00:28:52,910 --> 00:28:55,292
Have we proven that out yet?

533
00:28:56,513 --> 00:28:59,375
So we wanted to make these games as accessible as we could.

534
00:28:59,395 --> 00:29:03,559
We didn't want to just throw you in an 80s arcade and say, good luck, kid, right?

535
00:29:03,619 --> 00:29:08,423
Like we wanted you to be able to access this content without being good at old video games.

536
00:29:08,864 --> 00:29:11,546
And so if you want, you can just watch the games.

537
00:29:12,567 --> 00:29:17,568
So this is a playthrough, it's actually a fairly tool-assisted playthrough of me being

538
00:29:17,628 --> 00:29:20,909
more awesome than I actually am at playing these games.

539
00:29:21,389 --> 00:29:23,529
But like a movie, you can scrub through it, right?

540
00:29:24,049 --> 00:29:27,110
And you can go in there, you can pause, you can frame advance, you can frame rewind.

541
00:29:28,070 --> 00:29:31,911
It's all pixel perfect because this isn't a video, it's actually a button playback of

542
00:29:31,971 --> 00:29:32,411
the movie.

543
00:29:33,311 --> 00:29:38,633
So every frame, or maybe three frames, we're capturing basically a save state and then

544
00:29:38,673 --> 00:29:41,393
the button presses that come after it, and that's how we're able to scrub through it

545
00:29:41,433 --> 00:29:41,733
like that.

546
00:29:42,584 --> 00:29:42,727
Um...

547
00:29:43,928 --> 00:29:45,348
And because we did it that way,

548
00:29:46,548 --> 00:29:48,709
you don't have to just watch it forever.

549
00:29:48,729 --> 00:29:49,729
You don't have to be passive.

550
00:29:49,749 --> 00:29:51,510
You can actually just start playing

551
00:29:51,530 --> 00:29:53,210
because that's just a save state, right?

552
00:29:53,350 --> 00:29:56,891
So, to us, this was a way of letting you

553
00:29:57,051 --> 00:29:59,751
just flip through the game like it was a book

554
00:29:59,791 --> 00:30:01,612
and access whatever content you want to.

555
00:30:01,672 --> 00:30:06,893
And that was a fairly low-tech-ish way.

556
00:30:07,333 --> 00:30:10,094
I say low-tech and Adam, the programmer,

557
00:30:10,114 --> 00:30:11,854
is probably screaming if he's watching this.

558
00:30:14,515 --> 00:30:19,338
But, you know, it was our way of letting you access these parts of the game without having

559
00:30:19,378 --> 00:30:21,980
to heavily modify a binary file, right?

560
00:30:22,781 --> 00:30:27,484
But I think what was maybe the most important thing we did was reinterpreting some of the

561
00:30:27,524 --> 00:30:32,527
original arcade controls so that they made sense, not just to a modern player, but to

562
00:30:32,547 --> 00:30:34,308
a modern player on a modern controller.

563
00:30:35,990 --> 00:30:37,871
This is a rotary joystick.

564
00:30:37,931 --> 00:30:38,891
It's called the loop lever.

565
00:30:39,672 --> 00:30:41,332
SNK was known for this in the 80s.

566
00:30:41,932 --> 00:30:44,493
So just imagine this on an arcade machine.

567
00:30:46,114 --> 00:30:47,654
You tilt it like normal to move.

568
00:30:47,754 --> 00:30:48,635
It's a joystick, right?

569
00:30:48,655 --> 00:30:51,536
But you actually rotate the stick to aim.

570
00:30:52,516 --> 00:30:54,997
So, you know, here's Ikari Warriors, for example.

571
00:30:55,917 --> 00:30:57,118
There's only two buttons in the game.

572
00:30:57,878 --> 00:31:00,439
And you would, and they were nice enough

573
00:31:00,459 --> 00:31:02,059
to do a left and right hand configuration,

574
00:31:02,079 --> 00:31:02,540
which is kind of cool.

575
00:31:03,520 --> 00:31:08,525
But you would tilt to move your character around and you would twist to aim your gun

576
00:31:08,605 --> 00:31:09,526
and fire at people.

577
00:31:10,067 --> 00:31:13,830
And so playing Ikari Warriors, you know, is supposed to kind of look like this, right?

578
00:31:13,870 --> 00:31:19,856
Like you're able to sort of muscle memory your way in the original arcade game to be

579
00:31:19,896 --> 00:31:22,739
able to, you know, fire three o'clock and then point straight back up.

580
00:31:24,590 --> 00:31:30,552
Typically when this game has been re-released in the past, the way that that's been accomplished

581
00:31:30,632 --> 00:31:35,794
is to sort of map rotate clockwise and rotate counterclockwise to buttons and it just doesn't

582
00:31:35,834 --> 00:31:36,374
work that well.

583
00:31:36,454 --> 00:31:41,316
It doesn't feel like Ikari Warriors anymore and I actually think that the reason that

584
00:31:41,356 --> 00:31:46,117
fans don't talk about these games is because the only access we have had to them traditionally

585
00:31:46,177 --> 00:31:50,099
is through means like MAME where they don't play the way they're supposed to so they're

586
00:31:50,119 --> 00:31:50,299
not fun.

587
00:31:53,453 --> 00:31:57,034
So for our game, it may sound simple on paper,

588
00:31:57,074 --> 00:31:59,075
but we made it essentially a twin-stick shooter.

589
00:31:59,435 --> 00:32:03,097
So we're emulating the game just as it is on one layer,

590
00:32:03,137 --> 00:32:04,977
but there's an abstraction layer above it.

591
00:32:06,918 --> 00:32:09,119
So for example, if the player points straight down

592
00:32:09,199 --> 00:32:11,960
on the R stick, our abstraction layer

593
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:14,741
will tell the game, hey, change your game state

594
00:32:15,222 --> 00:32:16,862
so that the player is pointing straight down.

595
00:32:17,783 --> 00:32:20,404
There's no point straight down function

596
00:32:20,444 --> 00:32:21,684
in the original game, which is why

597
00:32:21,704 --> 00:32:23,045
we had to sort of interrupt the game.

598
00:32:23,805 --> 00:32:24,486
to tell it that.

599
00:32:25,227 --> 00:32:28,189
So essentially, we, I think, made Ikari Warriors

600
00:32:28,249 --> 00:32:31,673
playable for the first time since its arcade origins.

601
00:32:32,153 --> 00:32:33,274
So that makes sense, right?

602
00:32:33,394 --> 00:32:33,895
Easy to do.

603
00:32:34,675 --> 00:32:35,896
Hydrate's actually a good idea.

604
00:32:35,916 --> 00:32:37,918
If you guys need to hydrate, I think I do.

605
00:32:40,280 --> 00:32:42,142
All right, simple enough.

606
00:32:42,683 --> 00:32:43,363
What about the sequels?

607
00:32:43,383 --> 00:32:45,385
Ikari Warriors 3, The Rescue.

608
00:32:46,466 --> 00:32:47,187
Not a very good game.

609
00:32:49,087 --> 00:32:52,151
But it's not our job as historians to judge.

610
00:32:52,251 --> 00:32:55,134
It's our historians to report accurately.

611
00:32:55,655 --> 00:32:59,120
OK, so that's another rotary stick game, another rotary one.

612
00:32:59,160 --> 00:33:00,601
So moving kind of looks like this.

613
00:33:00,621 --> 00:33:02,924
You can aim where you want as you move

614
00:33:02,984 --> 00:33:04,386
and keep pointing in that direction.

615
00:33:05,207 --> 00:33:06,048
You've got a punch button.

616
00:33:07,427 --> 00:33:09,149
and you got a kick button, right?

617
00:33:09,869 --> 00:33:11,351
And then again, it's a rotary game.

618
00:33:11,431 --> 00:33:12,972
And what the game encouraged you to do

619
00:33:13,052 --> 00:33:15,034
were like roundhouse kicks, right?

620
00:33:15,495 --> 00:33:17,797
So using our existing setup, yeah, it kind of works.

621
00:33:17,817 --> 00:33:19,419
It doesn't feel that great, but you know,

622
00:33:19,439 --> 00:33:20,860
you kick and you rotate the R stick

623
00:33:20,900 --> 00:33:21,841
and you can do a roundhouse.

624
00:33:22,922 --> 00:33:24,283
In the arcade, much easier, right?

625
00:33:24,343 --> 00:33:25,745
Because you have one finger over here

626
00:33:25,805 --> 00:33:27,086
and you have a hand on the joystick.

627
00:33:27,106 --> 00:33:28,267
So it's just a simple motion.

628
00:33:29,989 --> 00:33:31,391
But wait, there's three buttons, right?

629
00:33:31,451 --> 00:33:35,256
So we no longer have our, uh, are just two buttons on the back.

630
00:33:35,276 --> 00:33:39,202
We have a jump button and with the jump button, you can jump kick.

631
00:33:39,803 --> 00:33:42,026
So, uh, again, this doesn't work.

632
00:33:42,567 --> 00:33:43,348
So, okay.

633
00:33:43,849 --> 00:33:43,949
Um,

634
00:33:44,890 --> 00:33:51,193
And what we did here was we basically combined the pointing with the R-stick with the moving

635
00:33:52,173 --> 00:33:56,455
and then put the three buttons on the face so that he now points where you walk like

636
00:33:56,475 --> 00:33:57,815
you would expect in most games.

637
00:33:58,536 --> 00:33:59,556
So that works pretty well.

638
00:33:59,716 --> 00:34:04,118
And because of that, you can actually now do the main move that the game expects you

639
00:34:04,158 --> 00:34:06,899
to do, which is a jumping roundhouse kick, right?

640
00:34:06,939 --> 00:34:08,399
Which of course you couldn't do.

641
00:34:09,600 --> 00:34:16,524
uh, actually, sorry, I skipped ahead, um, which you couldn't do, uh, if you had thumbs

642
00:34:16,584 --> 00:34:19,785
on two sticks and had to, like, press two buttons at the same, like, it just doesn't

643
00:34:19,825 --> 00:34:20,006
work.

644
00:34:20,626 --> 00:34:25,388
Um, game had another move, backhand, right, and that one is actually a jump punch.

645
00:34:25,869 --> 00:34:29,831
So, uh, jump punch on this controller, I didn't like the thumb movement.

646
00:34:30,511 --> 00:34:31,992
that was required to do that.

647
00:34:32,012 --> 00:34:34,514
I like the player to be able to just rest their thumb

648
00:34:34,594 --> 00:34:35,275
on kick and jump.

649
00:34:36,275 --> 00:34:38,517
And in the arcade game, again, we're thinking about

650
00:34:38,657 --> 00:34:40,518
how is the player playing this in the arcade game?

651
00:34:40,558 --> 00:34:42,379
If you think back to the way it was laid out,

652
00:34:42,820 --> 00:34:44,040
you'd have your hand on the joystick

653
00:34:44,061 --> 00:34:45,682
and you'd have three fingers on three buttons,

654
00:34:45,702 --> 00:34:47,063
so you could instantly do any of that.

655
00:34:47,343 --> 00:34:49,044
You can't do that if your thumb's just resting

656
00:34:49,184 --> 00:34:52,846
on jump and kick, so we added a backhand button.

657
00:34:52,887 --> 00:34:55,909
We just combined punch and jump into one button, so.

658
00:34:56,709 --> 00:34:57,550
Hooray, right?

659
00:34:57,750 --> 00:34:58,731
We solved all the problems.

660
00:34:59,372 --> 00:35:02,495
Oh, turns out that actually strafing is like a valid thing

661
00:35:02,535 --> 00:35:04,658
to do in this game, and we just took that away

662
00:35:04,718 --> 00:35:08,502
by combining the aiming and the moving into one stick.

663
00:35:09,082 --> 00:35:11,145
So this doesn't work anymore, right?

664
00:35:13,608 --> 00:35:15,510
But we don't want to take away the ability to jump kick,

665
00:35:15,530 --> 00:35:17,292
because that's actually the main move in the game.

666
00:35:18,153 --> 00:35:22,978
So what we went back and did was added an optional aim, right?

667
00:35:23,098 --> 00:35:25,400
So as you're tilting the left stick,

668
00:35:25,440 --> 00:35:27,342
he's moving and pointing in the way you're going.

669
00:35:27,642 --> 00:35:29,584
And if you happen to hit the R stick,

670
00:35:29,684 --> 00:35:31,847
he's then pointing wherever you're pointing that one.

671
00:35:32,187 --> 00:35:33,448
And then if you let go of the R stick,

672
00:35:33,468 --> 00:35:35,170
he just snaps back into the position

673
00:35:35,210 --> 00:35:36,191
that he was with the L stick.

674
00:35:38,651 --> 00:35:40,112
Can you guys see the problem here already?

675
00:35:40,472 --> 00:35:42,112
Like if you're shooting this gun, right?

676
00:35:42,172 --> 00:35:45,094
Like now your thumb is on the R-stick

677
00:35:45,874 --> 00:35:47,514
and how are you gonna point that

678
00:35:47,614 --> 00:35:50,176
and like curve your finger to shoot, right?

679
00:35:50,556 --> 00:35:53,277
So, okay, well we just added punch again.

680
00:35:53,297 --> 00:35:54,977
Like it's another button

681
00:35:55,398 --> 00:35:56,798
so you could easily shoot the gun.

682
00:35:57,718 --> 00:36:01,139
Wait, no, there's actually a secondary fire, which is throw your weapon.

683
00:36:01,199 --> 00:36:03,079
So let's just do backhand again.

684
00:36:05,240 --> 00:36:08,921
Like it looks really complicated, but I'd like to think it works.

685
00:36:09,221 --> 00:36:12,621
And that's just the level of thinking that I think you have to do

686
00:36:12,701 --> 00:36:16,162
to interpret these arcade games to play on controllers.

687
00:36:16,202 --> 00:36:17,682
They were never meant to play on.

688
00:36:18,282 --> 00:36:21,823
And if you were to play this game on MAME, you know, you could theoretically

689
00:36:21,923 --> 00:36:23,883
maybe get close to that setup on MAME.

690
00:36:24,384 --> 00:36:26,545
Or you can even on MAME, like, people

691
00:36:26,585 --> 00:36:28,767
have made new rotary controllers you can hook up to MAME,

692
00:36:28,787 --> 00:36:29,268
which is cool.

693
00:36:30,769 --> 00:36:33,251
But unless you know that's how the game functioned,

694
00:36:33,311 --> 00:36:34,872
unless you know that, you don't know

695
00:36:34,912 --> 00:36:36,973
to configure the game that way, right?

696
00:36:37,034 --> 00:36:40,176
And it's not MAME's job to sort of interpret.

697
00:36:40,296 --> 00:36:44,759
It's MAME's job to sort of be a binary equation, right?

698
00:36:46,080 --> 00:36:50,164
And so last time around, three years ago,

699
00:36:50,224 --> 00:36:51,925
I said we should maybe start using.

700
00:36:52,789 --> 00:36:54,530
MAME, because it's a solid emulator.

701
00:36:54,550 --> 00:36:56,632
It's got a lot of systems supported, it's open source.

702
00:36:57,032 --> 00:36:58,053
I don't think anyone's done that yet,

703
00:36:58,093 --> 00:36:59,073
that actually includes us.

704
00:36:59,274 --> 00:37:01,735
We haven't used MAME, the emulator, yet.

705
00:37:03,316 --> 00:37:05,157
But here's the thing, we're all using MAME.

706
00:37:06,358 --> 00:37:07,839
Every emulator author.

707
00:37:09,117 --> 00:37:11,419
in the commercial industry is using MAME.

708
00:37:11,919 --> 00:37:14,562
And I don't mean the executable emulator.

709
00:37:14,582 --> 00:37:16,363
I mean the MAME project.

710
00:37:16,423 --> 00:37:18,886
MAME is a documentation project.

711
00:37:19,006 --> 00:37:21,448
They document how these games and systems worked

712
00:37:21,748 --> 00:37:24,131
and put that information in an accessible place

713
00:37:24,151 --> 00:37:25,152
for people to reference.

714
00:37:26,653 --> 00:37:28,735
We're not doing this every time we do one of these collections.

715
00:37:28,755 --> 00:37:33,979
You know, we're not getting the original PCBs and like tracing the circuits and like,

716
00:37:34,179 --> 00:37:38,162
you know, like figuring out what the chips were and getting their specs and looking that up.

717
00:37:38,302 --> 00:37:43,486
And, you know, I mean, there's a little bit of that, but, but where we start is the MAME GitHub,

718
00:37:43,546 --> 00:37:47,710
right? Like, of course we would, why would we look at the physical object to figure that out

719
00:37:47,730 --> 00:37:52,313
when someone's already done that? We've all done that. And the reason we do that is it's simple.

720
00:37:52,333 --> 00:37:54,375
I mean, I'd like to think of MAME as the Wikipedia.

