happens to have purchased out the files of a marketing company that closed because he

953
00:51:02,297 --> 00:51:03,338
cares about this stuff.

954
00:51:03,398 --> 00:51:05,319
And that's the only reason we have this art.

955
00:51:07,160 --> 00:51:09,321
And that's, that's, to me, that's scary.

956
00:51:11,113 --> 00:51:14,676
But scariest to me of all is source, right?

957
00:51:15,977 --> 00:51:17,518
How many of you guys here work on games?

958
00:51:18,398 --> 00:51:18,779
Raise your hands.

959
00:51:18,819 --> 00:51:19,679
OK, keep your hands up.

960
00:51:20,640 --> 00:51:21,641
How many of I asked you?

961
00:51:22,141 --> 00:51:25,704
OK, so keep your hands up if you worked on a game that shipped

962
00:51:25,884 --> 00:51:27,485
five or more years ago, let's say.

963
00:51:28,706 --> 00:51:31,909
Franz, I know you did.

964
00:51:32,169 --> 00:51:34,350
OK, games five or more years ago.

965
00:51:34,811 --> 00:51:37,593
How many of you feel right now, if I asked you to,

966
00:51:37,653 --> 00:51:39,154
you can get that source and compile that game?

967
00:51:40,762 --> 00:51:41,584
Okay, few of you.

968
00:51:42,326 --> 00:51:43,569
The few of you that are left,

969
00:51:44,070 --> 00:51:46,716
how confident are you that 20 years from now,

970
00:51:47,237 --> 00:51:48,700
someone could not only locate that,

971
00:51:48,740 --> 00:51:50,705
but they could compile it and build it and it's right?

972
00:51:52,311 --> 00:51:53,211
Literally none of you.

973
00:51:53,791 --> 00:51:55,652
Literally zero people, right?

974
00:51:57,373 --> 00:51:59,934
And OK, let's make that even scarier.

975
00:52:00,394 --> 00:52:02,054
Digital Eclipse, the current incarnation,

976
00:52:02,094 --> 00:52:03,095
we've done these four products.

977
00:52:03,115 --> 00:52:05,575
50-ish classic arcade games.

978
00:52:06,016 --> 00:52:08,536
Out of those 50, how many would you

979
00:52:08,596 --> 00:52:10,497
suppose we had source access to?

980
00:52:11,758 --> 00:52:13,118
Zero is the correct answer.

981
00:52:13,138 --> 00:52:14,398
Did I tell you that?

982
00:52:17,779 --> 00:52:18,199
Zero.

983
00:52:19,740 --> 00:52:22,282
I'm not shaming companies when I say

984
00:52:22,302 --> 00:52:23,623
that it's just the reality.

985
00:52:23,663 --> 00:52:25,605
We didn't hold onto a lot of this source code.

986
00:52:27,467 --> 00:52:28,407
And that's terrifying.

987
00:52:28,868 --> 00:52:31,550
So, I'm speaking at a developers conference,

988
00:52:31,590 --> 00:52:32,631
ask developers what we can do.

989
00:52:32,671 --> 00:52:35,593
I'm gonna sort of bring back some wisdom from GDC's past.

990
00:52:35,633 --> 00:52:38,035
These are my pals, Lane Nooney and Jason Scott.

991
00:52:38,636 --> 00:52:40,918
I'm gonna let you figure out the order of operations here,

992
00:52:40,978 --> 00:52:41,899
but you're gonna steal from work

993
00:52:41,919 --> 00:52:43,000
and you're gonna put it in a box.

994
00:52:43,020 --> 00:52:44,761
You can do the box at work or you can do it at home.

995
00:52:44,821 --> 00:52:46,502
I don't care, just do both of those things.

996
00:52:47,583 --> 00:52:50,625
But don't forget that that material has to go somewhere,

997
00:52:50,665 --> 00:52:52,646
because if it's in your house forever

998
00:52:52,746 --> 00:52:56,289
and you get hit by a bus, just put it somewhere.

999
00:52:56,669 --> 00:52:57,850
There's a lot of places to put your stuff.

1000
00:53:00,051 --> 00:53:01,992
This list is nowhere near complete, obviously,

1001
00:53:02,092 --> 00:53:04,634
but these, for my money, are the best potential homes

1002
00:53:05,534 --> 00:53:06,915
for video game material.

1003
00:53:06,995 --> 00:53:10,237
So the Strong Museum of Play in Rochester, New York.

1004
00:53:11,138 --> 00:53:14,400
What I love about them is that they have a library in-house.

1005
00:53:14,420 --> 00:53:15,921
They have full-time librarians.

1006
00:53:16,281 --> 00:53:17,902
and they are actively collecting

1007
00:53:18,363 --> 00:53:19,924
video game development material.

1008
00:53:19,964 --> 00:53:22,025
So for example, Jordan Mechner,

1009
00:53:22,065 --> 00:53:24,147
who did Karateka, Prince of Persia, Last Express,

1010
00:53:25,568 --> 00:53:27,530
he donated all of his materials to The Strong.

1011
00:53:27,550 --> 00:53:29,251
And as a researcher, you can, and I have,

1012
00:53:29,611 --> 00:53:31,112
you can make an appointment with the library

1013
00:53:31,132 --> 00:53:32,734
and they'll bring out Jordan's material

1014
00:53:32,774 --> 00:53:34,715
and you can go through his design notes

1015
00:53:34,795 --> 00:53:38,018
and the video that he shot to rotoscope things.

1016
00:53:38,098 --> 00:53:41,801
Like you can access those materials and it's wonderful.

1017
00:53:41,821 --> 00:53:43,662
I really recommend that as an option.

1018
00:53:44,263 --> 00:53:46,404
The National Video Game Museum, Frisco, Texas.

1019
00:53:46,685 --> 00:53:51,068
They don't have a library yet, but these guys have been collecting this sort of ephemeral material

1020
00:53:51,529 --> 00:53:53,310
longer than anybody, like since the 90s.

1021
00:53:54,471 --> 00:53:59,555
And they've been, they're in what they call their sort of 1.0 phase of the museum right now,

1022
00:53:59,575 --> 00:54:01,357
which is more of a public-facing display.

1023
00:54:02,397 --> 00:54:04,779
But their expansion plans, should they raise enough money,

1024
00:54:05,139 --> 00:54:06,479
include opening a library.

1025
00:54:06,559 --> 00:54:08,700
So that's going to be a really viable option

1026
00:54:09,141 --> 00:54:09,901
when that happens.

1027
00:54:10,381 --> 00:54:11,922
The Internet Archive, if you don't give a damn,

1028
00:54:13,223 --> 00:54:14,623
if you're like, I don't care who has this,

1029
00:54:14,663 --> 00:54:16,864
just put it out there, that's your option right there.

1030
00:54:17,645 --> 00:54:19,225
Just pop it on the Internet Archive.

1031
00:54:19,425 --> 00:54:21,266
If you own the intellectual property, cool,

1032
00:54:21,346 --> 00:54:21,827
just put it there.

1033
00:54:22,007 --> 00:54:24,268
If you don't own it, I'm not a cop.

1034
00:54:25,168 --> 00:54:25,908
Put it on the internet.

1035
00:54:29,617 --> 00:54:30,717
Put it on the internet archive.

1036
00:54:30,757 --> 00:54:31,978
If you don't want to deal with it yourself,

1037
00:54:32,038 --> 00:54:34,639
find Jason Scott, who will do it for you.

1038
00:54:34,759 --> 00:54:37,920
And he'll do free PR to promote how amazing you are for putting

1039
00:54:37,940 --> 00:54:38,861
this material online.

1040
00:54:39,581 --> 00:54:41,242
Library of Congress is one we never talk about.

1041
00:54:42,482 --> 00:54:45,644
But they do have a video game archive in Culpeper, Virginia,

1042
00:54:45,684 --> 00:54:47,645
kind of remote, not the normal archive.

1043
00:54:47,685 --> 00:54:48,865
It's where their films are.

1044
00:54:50,166 --> 00:54:53,587
And they, believe it or not, could be a viable option.

1045
00:54:55,580 --> 00:54:57,081
They do seek material like this,

1046
00:54:58,262 --> 00:55:01,724
but they don't do a lot of outreach about it.

1047
00:55:01,944 --> 00:55:03,665
And I mean, this is the Library of Congress.

1048
00:55:03,685 --> 00:55:05,206
Their job is to take things, keep it safe.

1049
00:55:05,286 --> 00:55:06,847
And I've talked to them about it,

1050
00:55:06,867 --> 00:55:08,268
and they're like, yeah, we'll take source code.

1051
00:55:08,288 --> 00:55:09,029
We'll keep it safe.

1052
00:55:09,549 --> 00:55:11,610
I don't know that they necessarily have the infrastructure

1053
00:55:12,671 --> 00:55:15,453
to maintain source code or anything like that,

1054
00:55:15,493 --> 00:55:17,174
but I think that's something we could work toward.

1055
00:55:17,194 --> 00:55:19,235
I mean, I don't know, let's use our federal dollars

1056
00:55:19,275 --> 00:55:20,216
for a source repo.

1057
00:55:21,157 --> 00:55:21,537
Why not?

1058
00:55:23,278 --> 00:55:25,500
And finally, there's us, the Video Game History Foundation.

1059
00:55:25,520 --> 00:55:26,861
This is my baby.

1060
00:55:27,281 --> 00:55:28,522
So we're the newest of the bunch.

1061
00:55:28,842 --> 00:55:32,925
We just celebrated our two-year anniversary this week, I think.

1062
00:55:36,528 --> 00:55:37,808
So we're a 501c3.

1063
00:55:37,828 --> 00:55:40,971
We're just across the bridge in Emeryville, just down the street

1064
00:55:40,991 --> 00:55:41,471
from Pixar.

1065
00:55:44,814 --> 00:55:47,156
We are actually going to open a library there this year.

1066
00:55:47,176 --> 00:55:48,056
I haven't announced that.

1067
00:55:48,076 --> 00:55:48,717
I guess I just did.

1068
00:55:50,158 --> 00:55:52,520
But we're going to open by appointment.

1069
00:55:52,960 --> 00:55:55,062
I can't be a librarian 9 to 5.

1070
00:55:55,362 --> 00:55:58,145
But we're going to have a video game history reference

1071
00:55:58,165 --> 00:55:58,485
library.

1072
00:55:58,505 --> 00:56:00,707
I think it might be the first dedicated one.

1073
00:56:00,727 --> 00:56:01,748
That's all it's for.

1074
00:56:02,828 --> 00:56:03,509
So we're doing that.

1075
00:56:05,611 --> 00:56:07,352
If I'm wrong, if there's another video game

1076
00:56:07,913 --> 00:56:10,675
library for referencing this stuff, let me know.

1077
00:56:10,715 --> 00:56:11,215
I've got to visit.

1078
00:56:12,982 --> 00:56:15,243
I like to say we fill in the gaps with the other institutions.

1079
00:56:15,263 --> 00:56:16,904
Like we don't have to maintain a public museum.

1080
00:56:16,944 --> 00:56:21,026
I don't have to use my money for rent on a large space or conservation

1081
00:56:21,086 --> 00:56:23,768
of really crazy rare materials, things like that.

1082
00:56:23,808 --> 00:56:25,709
So we can be really flexible with our time and money.

1083
00:56:26,709 --> 00:56:27,790
But I think.

1084
00:56:28,671 --> 00:56:32,054
One of our best functions in the world

1085
00:56:32,154 --> 00:56:34,156
is to sort of provide an impartial voice

1086
00:56:34,417 --> 00:56:35,858
if you have materials like this.

1087
00:56:36,819 --> 00:56:39,282
So if you have your video game development material,

1088
00:56:39,322 --> 00:56:41,304
you don't know exactly where you want it to go,

1089
00:56:41,344 --> 00:56:42,285
but you want it to go somewhere,

1090
00:56:42,766 --> 00:56:44,107
I'll go through your options with you

1091
00:56:44,127 --> 00:56:46,169
and I'll tell you the pros and cons of each.

1092
00:56:46,189 --> 00:56:46,930
They're mostly pros,

1093
00:56:46,970 --> 00:56:49,072
but you know, I'll help you find the right home.

1094
00:56:50,934 --> 00:56:56,577
But I think our best place in the world is I want to work toward source material

1095
00:56:56,797 --> 00:56:58,357
being an educational resource.

1096
00:56:59,238 --> 00:57:01,779
I think the industry sees this stuff as a trade secret.

1097
00:57:01,879 --> 00:57:03,279
I think it's an educational tool.

1098
00:57:03,299 --> 00:57:06,521
I don't think there's a better way to understand a video game than to go back

1099
00:57:06,561 --> 00:57:09,282
to its source and to study it, maybe even rebuild it, right?

1100
00:57:10,603 --> 00:57:13,624
I want to live in a world where historians like me don't have to like reverse

1101
00:57:13,684 --> 00:57:14,784
engineer binaries.

1102
00:57:14,804 --> 00:57:15,565
This is stupid.

1103
00:57:17,363 --> 00:57:20,064
Like, if that source exists, why am I going out of my way

1104
00:57:20,104 --> 00:57:23,205
to circumvent that when the real thing exists?

1105
00:57:23,245 --> 00:57:24,826
It's kind of a new concept, I think.

1106
00:57:25,686 --> 00:57:27,687
Source code is an educational resource,

1107
00:57:28,147 --> 00:57:28,807
at least for games.

1108
00:57:28,827 --> 00:57:30,408
I don't think the traditional library system

1109
00:57:30,428 --> 00:57:32,448
really has language for that or tools yet,

1110
00:57:32,588 --> 00:57:34,629
but it's something we're trying to figure out.

1111
00:57:35,609 --> 00:57:36,910
But we're making it up as we go.

1112
00:57:37,070 --> 00:57:39,891
It's all brand new, figuring it out as we go.

1113
00:57:40,031 --> 00:57:42,592
But maybe we should figure it out together.

1114
00:57:44,432 --> 00:57:45,613
So if you're interested.

1115
00:57:47,591 --> 00:57:48,953
Let's get in touch, let's figure this out.

1116
00:57:48,993 --> 00:57:51,155
Let's figure out how to get our source material safe

1117
00:57:52,017 --> 00:57:55,861
and accessible and figure out where your comfort level is

1118
00:57:55,941 --> 00:57:57,083
on access, things like that.

1119
00:57:57,143 --> 00:57:57,984
Let's figure this out

1120
00:57:58,024 --> 00:58:00,407
because it's only gonna get harder as we go.

1121
00:58:02,189 --> 00:58:02,950
And that's it.

